related_questions.question: Are there any benefits to eating pecans?
related_questions.snippet: Pecans are High in Nutrients They're a good source of vitamin E, which is an antioxidant that protects your cells from damage. Pecans are also a good source of thiamine, which helps convert food into energy, and an excellent source of manganese, which is important for bone health and cell protection.
related_questions.title: Are Pecans Good for You? 7 Tasty Health Benefits of Pecans

related_questions.question: What is healthier walnuts or pecans?
related_questions.snippet: As you can see, walnuts and pecans are both winners in terms of nutritional value. While pecans have fewer calories and more fiber, walnuts offer a higher degree of protein. Whichever you choose, you'll enjoy heart-healthy nutrition with anti-inflammatory, antioxidant, and healthy cholesterol properties.
related_questions.title: Pecans vs. Walnuts - Glendas Farmhouse

related_questions.question: How many pecans can I eat a day?
related_questions.snippet: Recommendation: One ounce (15-19) pecan halves per day. Like pecans, walnuts are very high in antioxidants and contain more omega-3 fats than any other nut. Research has shown that eating moderate amounts of walnuts can aid in digestion, reduce risk of heart disease, decrease inflammation and support brain health.
related_questions.title: Can You Overdose on Nuts? | University Hospitals

related_questions.question: Is it better to eat almonds or pecans?
related_questions.snippet: Almonds have a higher mineral profile, while pecans are rich in minerals. Almond contains more calcium, magnesium, phosphorus, potassium, and iron than pecan, which has more zinc and less sodium. However, pecans have higher calories, fats, and thiamin (vitamin B1).
